{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:16:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:16:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15664"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15664"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.02,0,0.98]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114266"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8355"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96266"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22471"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114266"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe levator ani muscle is an integral part of the pelvic musculature.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Compresses the urethra only","Extends the lumbar spine","Flexes the hip joint","Rotates the thigh laterally","Supports pelvic viscera and maintains continence"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pelvic floor muscles play a crucial role in supporting pelvic organs and maintaining continence. Together with the coccygeus muscle and their associated fascias, the levator ani forms the pelvic diaphragm. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elevator ani\u003C/strong\u003E is the main muscle of the pelvic floor and has several important functions: supports the pelvic organs (bladder, uterus in women, rectum), maintains faecal and urinary continence, assists in increasing intra-abdominal pressure during forced expiration, and contracts during coughing, sneezing, and lifting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip flexion\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily performed by the iliopsoas muscle. \u003Cstrong\u003ELateral rotation of the thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the external rotator muscles of the hip. \u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar extension\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the erector spinae muscles. \u003Cstrong\u003EUrethral compression alone\u003C/strong\u003E is too narrow a description as the muscle has broader functions in pelvic support.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The levator ani forms the pelvic diaphragm and supports pelvic viscera while maintaining faecal and urinary continence.","The levator ani consists of three main parts: puborectalis, pubococcygeus, and iliococcygeus muscles."],"references":["Cheng LK, O\u0027Grady G, Du P, Egbuji JU, Windsor JA, Pullan AJ. Gastrointestinal system. Wiley Interdiscip Rev Syst Biol Med. 2010 Jan-Feb;2(1):65-79. doi: 10.1002/wsbm.19. PMID: 20836011; PMCID: PMC4221587.","Kahai P, Mandiga P, Wehrle CJ, Lobo S. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Large Intestine. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing, Treasure Island (FL); 2023. PMID: 29261962.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96266"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15664"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96266"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:30:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:30:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8355"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114266"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":